  <synthesis-reference/>
  <indication>Investigated for use/treatment in coronary artery disease, peripheral vascular disease, periodontal disease, bone fractures, entero-related fistulae, and diabetic foot ulcers.</indication>
  <pharmacodynamics/>
  <mechanism-of-action>Trafermin, or basic fibroblast growth factor 2 (bFGF) is a recombinant human growth factor used to stimulate angiogenesis and keratinization in wound healing. It stimulates migration of monocytes, neutrophils, macrophages, fibroblasts and also assists in creation of granulation tissue (the tissue that replaces fibrin clots in healing wounds).&#13;
&#13;
</mechanism-of-action>
